# Cloudflare Pages redirects.
#
# /blog and /blog/<slug> are static HTML pages that live at
# /blog/index.html and /blog/<slug>/index.html. The AEO Worker's
# `trailingSlash: 'never'` setting otherwise strips the trailing
# slash and creates a redirect loop with Cloudflare Pages' directory
# fallback (which expects a trailing slash for directory URLs).
#
# These status-200 rewrites fire BEFORE the Worker, so the browser
# stays at /blog (or /blog/<slug>) and the static file is served
# directly. No redirect chain, no loop.
#
# ─── Wrangler dev caveat ───────────────────────────────────────────
# `wrangler dev` (which uses `wrangler pages dev` under the hood
# for Pages projects) silently ignores `200` rewrites. It will show
# a 307↔301 redirect loop on /blog and /blog/<slug> in dev. This is
# a wrangler dev limitation, not a production issue. Per the AEO
# skill at https://hermes-agent.nousresearch.com/docs — confirmed
# that `_redirects` 200-rewrites work in production but are skipped
# in dev. Verify by deploying to a preview environment.
#
# If you need to test /blog locally: hit the static files directly.
# `python -m http.server dist/` on port 8124 will serve everything
# at the file path (no rewrites), so:
#   /blog/index.html                              ← the blog index
#   /blog/<slug>/index.html                       ← a blog post
#   /blog/index.md, /blog/<slug>.md               ← the markdown twins
# That's the structure Cloudflare Pages ASSETS sees.
/blog                                                     /blog/index.html                                                     200
/blog/how-to-validate-your-saas-idea-with-real-users      /blog/how-to-validate-your-saas-idea-with-real-users/index.html      200
